[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/fourth_suit_forcing"]
[Student "S"]
{You respond 2\C. Partner rebids 2\D. What is your next bid? 

With 13 HCP and that \C suit you could jump to 4\C. However, that would sail you right past 3NT which is very likely to turn out your best game. Rather than rebid \Cs, find out whether partner has \Ss stopped by using FSF.

You bid 2\S and partner then says 2NT. Where do you go from here? 

It couldn't have worked out better. Notrump played from partner's side. You bid 3NT.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "W:A863.AJ75.9.KQ64 4.T84.Q754.AJT52 KQ95.K3.AJ863.93 JT72.Q962.KT2.87"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
1C pass 1D pass 1H pass 1S pass 2S pass 4S all pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "93d931e350ae4ccf1245f8a870025abf0608dded8228128bf55eaa4e756cc1df"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/fourth_suit_forcing"]
[Student "S"]
{There is only one possibility; you open 1\C. Partner responds 1\D.  

You rebid "up-the-line", so you now say 1\H. Partner says 1\S.  

Be careful! This is NOT Fourth Suit Forcing. It is true that you are forced to bid, but the difference is that in this sequence partner has a real \S suit. With 4-card support you bid 2\S and partner raises to 4\S.}

